One method of distinguishing between true and false prophecies appears to have been the use of acrostics in the latter. Thus Cicero (De Dio. ii. 111) argues that such an artificial form of composition is inconsistent with the divine frenzy ascribed to the Sibyl, and, Varro is quoted to the same effect by Dion. Hal. (Α. R. iv. 62), as saying that the spurious oracles may be detected hythe socalled acrostics.1
